57#ifndef OPENSSL_HEADER_OBJ_H
58#define OPENSSL_HEADER_OBJ_H
59
60#include <openssl/base.h>
61
62#include <openssl/bytestring.h>
63#include <openssl/nid.h>
64
65#if defined(__cplusplus)
66extern "C" {
67#endif
68
69
70// The objects library deals with the registration and indexing of ASN.1 object
71// identifiers. These values are often written as a dotted sequence of numbers,
72// e.g. 1.2.840.113549.1.9.16.3.9.
73//
74// Internally, OpenSSL likes to deal with these values by numbering them with
75// numbers called "nids". OpenSSL has a large, built-in database of common
76// object identifiers and also has both short and long names for them.
77//
78// This library provides functions for translating between object identifiers,
79// nids, short names and long names.
80//
81// The nid values should not be used outside of a single process: they are not
82// stable identifiers.
83
84
85// Basic operations.
86
87// OBJ_dup returns a duplicate copy of |obj| or NULL on allocation failure.
88OPENSSL_EXPORT ASN1_OBJECT *OBJ_dup(const ASN1_OBJECT *obj);
89
90// OBJ_cmp returns a value less than, equal to or greater than zero if |a| is
91// less than, equal to or greater than |b|, respectively.
92OPENSSL_EXPORT int OBJ_cmp(const ASN1_OBJECT *a, const ASN1_OBJECT *b);
93
94// OBJ_get0_data returns a pointer to the DER representation of |obj|. This is
95// the contents of the DER-encoded identifier, not including the tag and length.
96// If |obj| does not have an associated object identifier (i.e. it is a nid-only
97// value), this value is the empty string.
98OPENSSL_EXPORT const uint8_t *OBJ_get0_data(const ASN1_OBJECT *obj);
99
100// OBJ_length returns the length of the DER representation of |obj|. This is the
101// contents of the DER-encoded identifier, not including the tag and length. If
102// |obj| does not have an associated object identifier (i.e. it is a nid-only
103// value), this value is the empty string.
104OPENSSL_EXPORT size_t OBJ_length(const ASN1_OBJECT *obj);
105
106
107// Looking up nids.
108
109// OBJ_obj2nid returns the nid corresponding to |obj|, or |NID_undef| if no
110// such object is known.
111OPENSSL_EXPORT int OBJ_obj2nid(const ASN1_OBJECT *obj);
112
113// OBJ_cbs2nid returns the nid corresponding to the DER data in |cbs|, or
114// |NID_undef| if no such object is known.
115OPENSSL_EXPORT int OBJ_cbs2nid(const CBS *cbs);
116
117// OBJ_sn2nid returns the nid corresponding to |short_name|, or |NID_undef| if
118// no such short name is known.
119OPENSSL_EXPORT int OBJ_sn2nid(const char *short_name);
120
121// OBJ_ln2nid returns the nid corresponding to |long_name|, or |NID_undef| if
122// no such long name is known.
123OPENSSL_EXPORT int OBJ_ln2nid(const char *long_name);
124
125// OBJ_txt2nid returns the nid corresponding to |s|, which may be a short name,
126// long name, or an ASCII string containing a dotted sequence of numbers. It
127// returns the nid or NID_undef if unknown.
128OPENSSL_EXPORT int OBJ_txt2nid(const char *s);
129
130
131// Getting information about nids.
132
133// OBJ_nid2obj returns the |ASN1_OBJECT| corresponding to |nid|, or NULL if
134// |nid| is unknown.
135//
136// This function returns a static, immutable |ASN1_OBJECT|. Although the output
137// is not const, callers may not mutate it. It is also not necessary to release
138// the object with |ASN1_OBJECT_free|.
139//
140// However, functions like |X509_ALGOR_set0| expect to take ownership of a
141// possibly dynamically-allocated |ASN1_OBJECT|. |ASN1_OBJECT_free| is a no-op
142// for static |ASN1_OBJECT|s, so |OBJ_nid2obj| is compatible with such
143// functions.
144//
145// Callers are encouraged to store the result of this function in a const
146// pointer. However, if using functions like |X509_ALGOR_set0|, callers may use
147// a non-const pointer and manage ownership.
148OPENSSL_EXPORT ASN1_OBJECT *OBJ_nid2obj(int nid);
149
150// OBJ_nid2sn returns the short name for |nid|, or NULL if |nid| is unknown.
151OPENSSL_EXPORT const char *OBJ_nid2sn(int nid);
152
153// OBJ_nid2ln returns the long name for |nid|, or NULL if |nid| is unknown.
154OPENSSL_EXPORT const char *OBJ_nid2ln(int nid);
155
156// OBJ_nid2cbb writes |nid| as an ASN.1 OBJECT IDENTIFIER to |out|. It returns
157// one on success or zero otherwise.
158OPENSSL_EXPORT int OBJ_nid2cbb(CBB *out, int nid);
159
160
161// Dealing with textual representations of object identifiers.
162
163// OBJ_txt2obj returns an ASN1_OBJECT for the textual representation in |s|.
164// If |dont_search_names| is zero, then |s| will be matched against the long
165// and short names of a known objects to find a match. Otherwise |s| must
166// contain an ASCII string with a dotted sequence of numbers. The resulting
167// object need not be previously known. It returns a freshly allocated
168// |ASN1_OBJECT| or NULL on error.
169OPENSSL_EXPORT ASN1_OBJECT *OBJ_txt2obj(const char *s, int dont_search_names);
170
171// OBJ_obj2txt converts |obj| to a textual representation. If
172// |always_return_oid| is zero then |obj| will be matched against known objects
173// and the long (preferably) or short name will be used if found. Otherwise
174// |obj| will be converted into a dotted sequence of integers. If |out| is not
175// NULL, then at most |out_len| bytes of the textual form will be written
176// there. If |out_len| is at least one, then string written to |out| will
177// always be NUL terminated. It returns the number of characters that could
178// have been written, not including the final NUL, or -1 on error.
179OPENSSL_EXPORT int OBJ_obj2txt(char *out, int out_len, const ASN1_OBJECT *obj,
180 int always_return_oid);
181
182
183// Adding objects at runtime.
184
185// OBJ_create adds a known object and returns the nid of the new object, or
186// NID_undef on error.
187OPENSSL_EXPORT int OBJ_create(const char *oid, const char *short_name,
188 const char *long_name);
189
190
191// Handling signature algorithm identifiers.
192//
193// Some NIDs (e.g. sha256WithRSAEncryption) specify both a digest algorithm and
194// a public key algorithm. The following functions map between pairs of digest
195// and public-key algorithms and the NIDs that specify their combination.
196//
197// Sometimes the combination NID leaves the digest unspecified (e.g.
198// rsassaPss). In these cases, the digest NID is |NID_undef|.
199
200// OBJ_find_sigid_algs finds the digest and public-key NIDs that correspond to
201// the signing algorithm |sign_nid|. If successful, it sets |*out_digest_nid|
202// and |*out_pkey_nid| and returns one. Otherwise it returns zero. Any of
203// |out_digest_nid| or |out_pkey_nid| can be NULL if the caller doesn't need
204// that output value.
205OPENSSL_EXPORT int OBJ_find_sigid_algs(int sign_nid, int *out_digest_nid,
206 int *out_pkey_nid);
207
208// OBJ_find_sigid_by_algs finds the signature NID that corresponds to the
209// combination of |digest_nid| and |pkey_nid|. If success, it sets
210// |*out_sign_nid| and returns one. Otherwise it returns zero. The
211// |out_sign_nid| argument can be NULL if the caller only wishes to learn
212// whether the combination is valid.
213OPENSSL_EXPORT int OBJ_find_sigid_by_algs(int *out_sign_nid, int digest_nid,
214 int pkey_nid);
215
216
217// Deprecated functions.
218
219typedef struct obj_name_st {
220 int type;
221 int alias;
222 const char *name;
223 const char *data;
224} OBJ_NAME;
225
226#define OBJ_NAME_TYPE_MD_METH 1
227#define OBJ_NAME_TYPE_CIPHER_METH 2
228
229// OBJ_NAME_do_all_sorted calls |callback| zero or more times, each time with
230// the name of a different primitive. If |type| is |OBJ_NAME_TYPE_MD_METH| then
231// the primitives will be hash functions, alternatively if |type| is
232// |OBJ_NAME_TYPE_CIPHER_METH| then the primitives will be ciphers or cipher
233// modes.
234//
235// This function is ill-specified and should never be used.
236OPENSSL_EXPORT void OBJ_NAME_do_all_sorted(
237 int type, void (*callback)(const OBJ_NAME *, void *arg), void *arg);
238
239// OBJ_NAME_do_all calls |OBJ_NAME_do_all_sorted|.
240OPENSSL_EXPORT void OBJ_NAME_do_all(int type, void (*callback)(const OBJ_NAME *,
241 void *arg),
242 void *arg);
243
244// OBJ_cleanup does nothing.
245OPENSSL_EXPORT void OBJ_cleanup(void);
246
247
248#if defined(__cplusplus)
249} // extern C
250#endif

252#define OBJ_R_UNKNOWN_NID 100
253#define OBJ_R_INVALID_OID_STRING 101
254
255#endif // OPENSSL_HEADER_OBJ_H
